  "review": "This paper introduces Graph Edit Networks (GENs), a novel output layer for graph neural networks that predicts sequences of graph edits to transform input graphs to output graphs. The approach is well-motivated by the gap in graph-to-graph learning, particularly for time series prediction. Key strengths include: (1) Theoretically grounded design, with proofs showing that node mappings suffice for training and that optimal mappings yield edit scripts close to the graph edit distance. (2) Sparsity and locality of edits, enabling linear-time complexity and avoiding pooling layers. (3) Strong empirical validation on graph dynamical systems (edit cycles, degree rules, Game of Life) and tree tasks (Boolean, Peano), where GENs outperform VGAE/VGRNN baselines in precision/recall for node/edge edits. Weaknesses: (1) Limited exploration of non-Markovian settings; the suggestion to integrate with EvolveGCN is not experimentally validated. (2) Experiments rely on synthetic data; real-world scalability beyond 2.7k nodes (HEP-Th) is underexplored. (3) Theoretical 'near-optimality' assumes optimal node mapping approximation, which is NP-hard. Actionable suggestions: (1) Extend to recurrent architectures (e.g., EvolveGCN) for historical context. (2) Evaluate on real-world temporal graphs (e.g., social networks). (3) Analyze sensitivity to suboptimal mappings in training.",
